 Is consciousness a causative agent in the physical world? With much progress being made in the neurosciences, many have thought that these questions could be answered by reducing them to questions about physical systems such as the brain. But this approach has foundered on the core problem of consciousness: Why is it that some brain processes are accompanied by conscious awareness? This anthology points out new sources and unexamined paths of consciousness research. By presenting a wide spectrum of non-reductive theories, the volume endeavours to overcome the dichotomy between dualism and monism that keeps plaguing the debate in favour of new and more differentiated positions.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aConsciousness. 0aMind and body. 4aOntologie. 4aPhilosophie des Geistes. 4aPhilosophie. 7aPHILOSOPHY / History & Surveys / General.2bisacsh1 aArnette, J. Kenneth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBatthyany, Alexander, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBatthyány, Alexander, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aEdge, Hoyt, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aElitzur, Avshalom, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aElitzur, Avshalom, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKing, Peter J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKurizki, Gershon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLehar, Steven, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLloyd, Peter B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLøvland, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aManzotti, Riccardo, 